  },
  keywords = {Marx, unalienated-labor, recognition, social-contribution, High},
  abstract = {Marx’s vision of unalienated production is often thought to be subject to decisive objections. This article argues that these objections rely on a misinterpretation of Marx’s position. It provides a new interpretation of Marx’s vision of unalienated production. Unlike another well-known account, it suggests that unalienated production involves realizing oneself through providing others with the goods and services they need for their self-realization. It argues that this view is appealing and that it offers a more successful response to objections than previous interpretations. In doing so, it hopes to put Marx’s concern with alienation and nonalienation back on the table.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
  sep_context = {SEP "Alienation" entry cites Kandiyali (2020) to characterize unalienated/meaningful work in communist society as: freely chosen, involving self-realization (developing essential human powers), intended to satisfy others' needs, and appropriately appreciated by those others. This contrasts with alienated labor under capitalism which is forced, prevents self-realization, is not intended to satisfy others' needs, and is not appropriately appreciated. The SEP uses Kandiyali to articulate Marx's positive vision of unalienated work as essentially social and recognition-based.},}

@article{vanderdeijl2022two,
  author = {van der Deijl, Willem},
  title = {Two Concepts of Meaningful Work},
  journal = {Journal of Applied Philosophy},
  year = {2022},
  volume = {41},
  number = {2},
  pages = {202--217},
  doi = {10.1111/japp.12614},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Distinguishes two concepts of meaningful work: quality (work good for the worker—autonomous, engaging, skill-using) and significance (work good for others—making valuable contributions). These can come apart: assembly line work may have high significance (producing needed goods) but low quality; an engaging hobby may have high quality but low significance. Both dimensions matter, but political philosophy should prioritize ensuring significance-work opportunities (contributive justice) over quality-work.

  RELEVANCE: This distinction directly addresses the DIY question by separating process-value (quality) from outcome-value (significance). Doing things yourself may preserve quality-meaningfulness (autonomous engagement) but sacrifice significance-meaningfulness (social contribution) if the outcome serves only yourself. Van der Deijl's prioritization of significance over quality suggests delegation may be preferable when it enables greater social contribution. However, this assumes the activity is work rather than leisure.

  POSITION: Recent contribution distinguishing two dimensions of meaningful work. Outcome-oriented insofar as it prioritizes significance, but recognizes quality's importance. Medium-high importance for conceptual clarity.
  },
  keywords = {meaningful-work, quality-significance, contributive-justice, High},
  abstract = {ABSTRACT The concept of meaningful work is used to evaluate the quality of work. Typical cases of meaningless work that have been used to clarify this concept are assembly line work, and work involving other types of mindless tasks, but also David Graeber's ‘bullshit jobs’. I argue that there are at least two fundamental reasons to care about meaningful work: reasons from the wellbeing of the worker and reasons pertaining to meaningfulness of the worker's life. I first argue that a concept of meaningful work needs to reflect these two values, but that these two values may come apart. Because of this, accounts that provide a single answer to the question to what extent a particular work context is meaningful work for a particular worker are unable to reflect these two values. I then survey three promising accounts of meaningful work: perfectionism, which captures the self‐interested aspect of meaningful work well but fails to capture the meaningfulness aspect appropriately; consequentialism, which captures the meaningfulness aspect well but fails to capture the self‐interested aspect; and Wolf's Fitting Fulfilment View of meaningful projects, which can be read as addressing both concerns but leads to implausible judgments about meaningful work. I then argue that we should conceive of the concerns that fall under the notion of meaningful work as two separate concepts and values. The best work incorporates both these dimensions but falling short on either dimension is problematic for different reasons.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
}

@article{althorpe2022meaningful,
  author = {Althorpe, Caleb},
  title = {Meaningful Work, Nonperfectionism, and Reciprocity},
  journal = {Critical Review of International Social and Political Philosophy},
  year = {2022},
  volume = {28},
